      <a href="https://cursor.sh" class="btn btn-secondary" target="_blank">Try Cursor Free →</a>
    </div>

    <h2>Quick Comparison</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>GitHub Copilot</th><th>Cursor</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Best For</td><td>Inline code completion</td><td>AI-native coding environment</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Platform</td><td>VS Code, JetBrains, Neovim</td><td>Standalone IDE (VS Code fork)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Context</td><td>Current file + open tabs</td><td>Full codebase indexing</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pro Price</td><td>$10/mo (Individual)</td><td>$20/mo (Pro)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Free Tier</td><td>30-day trial</td><td>Limited, 2000 completions/mo</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Chat Features</td><td>Basic chat in sidebar</td><td>Built-in AI chat with context</td></tr>
        
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>What Is GitHub Copilot?</h2>
    <h2>What Is GitHub Copilot?</h2>
    <p>GitHub Copilot was launched in 2021 as a partnership between GitHub and OpenAI. It became the first widely adopted AI coding assistant, supporting VS Code, JetBrains IDEs, Neovim, and Visual Studio. Copilot provides inline code suggestions as developers type, learning from context in the current file and open tabs. It includes a chat feature for asking coding questions. The Individual plan costs $10 per month, with a 30-day free trial. Copilot is also available through GitHub Enterprise for organizations at $19 per user per month.</p>
    <h2>What Is Cursor?</h2>
    <h2>What Is Cursor?</h2>
    <p>Cursor is a newer entrant, launched in 2023 as an AI-first code editor built on a fork of VS Code. Unlike Copilot which adds AI to an existing editor, Cursor is designed from the ground up for AI-assisted development. Its key innovation is full codebase indexing, allowing the AI to understand how all files in your project relate to each other. Cursor offers natural language editing commands, inline code suggestions, and a powerful chat interface that references your entire project. Cursor Pro costs $20 per month.</p>
    <h2>Feature-by-Feature Comparison</h2>
    <h2>Feature-by-Feature Comparison</h2>
    <h3>Code Completion and Suggestions</h3>
    <p>GitHub Copilot provides excellent inline code completion that feels natural within existing workflows. Suggestions appear as gray text while you type, based on context from the current file and recently opened files. Cursor offers comparable inline completion but adds the ability to edit code through natural language commands directly in the editor. For traditional tab-to-complete workflows, Copilot's integration with existing IDEs is more seamless. For AI-native editing, Cursor's natural language commands are more powerful.</p>

    <h3>Codebase Understanding</h3>
    <p>Cursor's full codebase indexing provides significantly better context awareness. The AI understands how functions in one file are called in another, the structure of your database schemas, and the relationships between components. This makes Cursor's suggestions more coherent across larger projects. Copilot is limited to the current file and open tabs, giving it less context for cross-file operations. For solo projects, both work well. For complex multi-file codebases, Cursor's understanding is meaningfully superior.</p>

    <h3>Chat and AI Interaction</h3>
    <p>Cursor's AI chat has access to your entire codebase context. You can ask questions about application architecture, find relevant code across files, and request changes that span multiple files — the AI understands the full project structure. Copilot's chat is more limited in context but still useful for quick questions about the current file. For developers who rely on AI for codebase exploration and cross-file operations, Cursor's contextual chat is significantly more capable.</p>

    <h3>IDE Flexibility</h3>
    <p>GitHub Copilot works across multiple IDEs (VS Code, JetBrains, Neovim, Visual Studio), making it suitable for developers who switch between editors or work in languages with different IDE requirements. Cursor is a standalone editor that requires switching from your current development environment. This is a meaningful barrier for developers invested in other IDEs. For multi-IDE developers, Copilot's broader platform support is more practical.</p>
    <h2>Performance and User Experience</h2>
    <h2>Performance and User Experience</h2>
    <p>GitHub Copilot's inline suggestions appear within 500ms-1s and feel responsive during active typing. The chat interface loads in 2-3 seconds. Cursor's inline suggestions are similarly fast, but its codebase indexing adds initial startup time — indexing a moderate-sized project (10,000 files) takes 30-60 seconds on first load. Subsequent operations benefit from cached indexing. Cursor's natural language code editing operations take 3-8 seconds depending on the scope of changes across files. For quick inline completions, both perform similarly. For larger AI-assisted operations, Cursor's understanding of the codebase produces more coherent results despite slightly slower response times.</p>
    <h2>Pricing Comparison</h2>
    <h2>Pricing Comparison</h2>
    <p>GitHub Copilot Individual costs $10 per month, with a 30-day free trial. Copilot Business costs $19 per user per month with organization-wide policy management. Copilot Enterprise adds $39 per user per month with customized models. Cursor Pro costs $20 per month, about double Copilot's individual plan. Cursor Business at $40 per user per month adds team-admin controls. A limited free tier is available with 2,000 code completions per month. For individual developers, Copilot is significantly cheaper. For developers who value codebase-aware AI assistance, Cursor's higher price is justified by its superior project understanding.</p>
    <h2>Pros and Cons</h2>

    <h3>GitHub Copilot Pros</h3>
    <div class="pros-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Works across multiple IDEs</li>
        <li>Excellent inline completions</li>
        <li>Lower price than Cursor</li>
        <li>Seamless VS Code setup</li>
        <li>Backed by GitHub/OpenAI</li>
        <li>Regular updates and active development</li>
        <li>Strong community and support resources</li>
        
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>GitHub Copilot Cons</h3>
    <div class="cons-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Limited codebase understanding</li>
        <li>Chat features less powerful</li>
        <li>Cannot edit across multiple files</li>
        <li>Occasional irrelevant suggestions</li>
        <li>Learning curve for advanced features</li>
        <li>Some integrations still maturing</li>
        
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Cursor Pros</h3>
    <div class="pros-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Full codebase indexing</li>
        <li>Powerful AI chat with project context</li>
        <li>Natural language code editing</li>
        <li>Multi-file refactoring support</li>
        <li>Designed for AI workflows</li>
        <li>Active development and frequent updates</li>
        <li>Growing community and ecosystem</li>
        
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Cursor Cons</h3>
    <div class="cons-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Requires switching editors</li>
        <li>Higher price than Copilot</li>
        <li>Newer, smaller community</li>
        <li>Some VS Code extensions incompatible</li>
        <li>Learning curve for new workflow</li>
        <li>Interface can feel overwhelming initially</li>
        <li>Premium features require higher tier plans</li>
        
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Who Should Use Which?</h2>
    <p><strong>Choose GitHub Copilot</strong> if you want AI assistance within your existing IDE at a lower price point.</p>
    <p><strong>Choose Cursor</strong> if you want the most powerful AI coding experience and can switch to a dedicated AI-first editor.</p>

    <h2>Real-World Use Cases</h2>

      <div class="use-case">
    <h3>Full-Stack Developers</h3>
    <p>Cursor codebase understanding helps with complex multi-file projects.</p>
  </div>
    <div class="use-case">
    <h3>Beginners</h3>
    <p>Copilot simpler integration with familiar IDEs makes it more accessible.</p>
  </div>
    <div class="use-case">
    <h3>Enterprise Teams</h3>
    <p>Copilot wider IDE support and lower per-user cost make it better for teams.</p>
  </div>
    <div class="use-case">
    <h3>Open Source</h3>
    <p>Both work well. Copilot GitHub integration is convenient for PRs and issues.</p>
  </div>
  

